w:r.w:t: This document presents an example of the use case model structure proposed for managing varibilities in requirements documents. The scenarios shown here, which were also presented at AOSD 09, describe part of the specifications for an electronic commerce product line.
The main difference between the current
and the proposal discussed here is that the new version of the use case model represents variant behavior in terms of aspects and advices.
Use cases that allow a customer to search and buy goods. These use cases describe the common behavior of the product line.
It describes the common behavior related to confirming a purchase.
: This behavior corresponds to the last steps required to confirm a purchase.
Request the shipping method and address.
Execute the order and send a request to the Delivery System, in order to dispatch the products.
It describes the behavior that allows a customer to search products.
Request the customer to inform the search criteria.
Retrieve the products that satisfy the search criteria. Show a list with the corresponding products.
Use cases that allow a customer to search and buy goods. These use cases describe the common behavior of the product line.
It describes the behavior that allows a customer to buy a single product.
Present the selected product. The user can change the quantity of items he wants to buy.
It describes the behavior that allows a customer to buy product using a shopping cart.
Description: Buy products using a shopping cart
Present the items in the shopping cart and the amount to be paid. The customer can remove items from his (her) shopping cart.
Register the user preferences, based on her (his) historical data of searching and purchasing.
Update the customer preferences based on the search results or purchased items.
